node.text: Boundaries, self talk, and what to do when we hurt someone close to us are just a few of the things that we cover today. For those interested, two useful books from this week's answers are Chatter by @ethankross on the inner voice of our minds, and Where to Draw the Line by Anne Katherine on boundaries. I also reference @monkmanual as a great tool for routine and habit setting as well as breaking habits. Enjoy! In partnership w @roam

node.text: Boundaries, self talk, and what to do when we hurt someone close to us are just a few of the things that we cover today. For those interested, two useful books from this week's answers are Chatter by @ethankross on the inner voice of our minds, and Where to Draw the Line by Anne Katherine on boundaries. I also reference @monkmanual as a great tool for routine and habit setting as well as breaking habits. Enjoy! In partnership w @roam

node.text: Mental Health, Bipolar, and Suicide...let's talk about it. In this little three part series, I want to blow open the discussion about what a bipolar episode can look like, how to handle it from both the perspective of the person suffering and those who are managing it externally, and disarm the stigma around what this looks and feels like holistically.  I'm reticent at best to share so openly about what I've been going through. Rather, I'd hope this can be taken as an opportunity to use my platform to dive into the acute nature of these things, discussing them candidly in order to further normalize the conversation at large. I've tried to speak as objectively as possible while still sharing the depths of these experiences in hopes that we can begin to understand just how complex this topic is. Let me know your thoughts and feedback. This is for you. #mentalhealth #mentalhealthawareness #mentalhealthmondays

node.text: Loba women of Mustang stand for a portrait in traditional clothing set against the modern footings of a new structure, part of ongoing development in the region. For this assignment for @natgeo I wanted to juxtapose what was against what is in surprising ways that would help illustrate the immediacy of the change taking place. Much of the development is badly needed and provides access to resources previously unavailable or incredibly hard to reach. But with development come the hurdles of cultural erosion and the loss of cultural identity. No easy answers, but lots of good questions. #onassignment @jetbutterflies @lkcvt @standtallest @sadiequarrier

node.text: Back at it!! Welcome back to #mentalhealthmondays with @rhone Great @nytimes article by @kelleymcmillanmanley on this springs expedition and the resultant debate regarding mental health. I thought this article was beautifully articulated and well thought out. For so many, speaking openly about mental health is difficult if not seemingly impossible. This article was a fair and insightful look at the complexity mental health issues present. Nothing about the topic is 'easy', but the more conversation we have, the further down the road we get. Some of the provided commentary stings a bit, but I'm also understanding of it. If anything, it only underscores the uphill battle mental health as an issue faces. I've spoken openly and at length for years as an advocate for mental health and wellness, and I believe this article is a fabulous deepening of that journey. Thanks @nytimes and @kelleymcmillanmanley for the effort and research. Link in bio for the whole article. #mentalhealthmondays @rhone

node.text: 49 years. Growing up, sitting in the distance that a child has from the complications of relationships and marriage, it always appeared that my parents loved each other. I believe they still do on this day 49 years after they made promises that their younger selves could hardly comprehend. My current view allows for the scar tissue of entanglement and codependence as well as the nuance (as much as I can relate) to how complex making a life with someone really is. Decades pass. People grow and change. As a child though, watching them holding hands across the console of our red Ford van as it lumbered through the auburn Utah desert, Paul Simon's Graceland blaring and my mother twisting a strand of sandy hair, they appeared as one. I know now how complicated a couple holding hands can be. Sometimes an act of solidarity, and sometimes clinging desperation. For them, and I believe for all couples who make it this far, it has been both. At times, I'm sure they wanted to let go...even did. But now, I watch them hold tightly to the waning moments that life has left for them as a couple. In that clasp, nothing has changed, but everything is different. I'm so proud of them. I'm so grateful that they have chosen to continue the journey together to its inevitable end. Thank you for choosing eachother. Thank you for hanging on. I love you both. Happy Anniversary.

node.text: My dad is still alive and actually doing really well in the face of terminal cancer...and still, I miss him. I have a sinking feeling that this is the nature of dying. We only know what we should've said, should've done. The invitation to stare into it as it happens is unassuming, quiet, and does not come with reminders. And for most of us, the courage that is required to do so escapes us. So we let it happen in silence, wishing after the fact that we had taken even just one moment longer in every interaction, adding up to a mountain of minutes that live as ghosts of memories we never made. We miss the person as they live on, lost for words and afraid to stumble in the unfamiliar certainty of passing. I love my father. I love his hands and his teary eyes. I miss his wandering answers and his familiar humor, tired and worn like a sweat stained hat. I remember the smell of his workshop in our garage. His laugh. His faded stories, repeated because he stopped making new ones long ago. I miss him as he wanders in life towards an end we can all see but can never comprehend. I miss him as I sit in an airplane, suspended above a million fathers and sons and daughters, all stumbling over the words they want to speak but never do. I love everything about you dad.

node.text: When I started making pictures 22 years ago, I had no idea where it would lead. I knew that I wanted and would make pictures for @natgeo but I had no idea how. So I just made pictures. Of everything. This is an image shot on film at an underground fetish fashion show in Seattle. I remember the light and darkness, the chaos, the unbridled sexuality, and the smoke. I remember feeling out of place as I moved through the crowd behind the stage and timidly made pictures of people and costumes. It was all foreign to me. Pouring over work now, I see that I wasn't completely lost, however. There was vision and I was seeing. I get asked all the time 'how do I get in?' And the simplest answer is you find your way. There isn't a singular path. But by asking the question, you can be sure that you're on one. It doesn't mean that you'll end up where you thought you were headed, but you will end up where you're going. I feel this same sense of angst now as I transition into my next chapter. I see the mountain top and I know I'll get there...but how is anyone's guess. This is all to say that perhaps the most important thing we can do as we embark on our respective journeys is to trust the process. Because that's where all the good sh*t is anyway.

node.text: A still life of a monastic text of the the life of the Buddha is lit by candlelight in the interior of a Monastery, Nepal. The cover of the book is adorned by 108 hand carved Buddhas and it's hundreds of pages include intricate illuminations (paintings) of the Buddhas life and teachings. Some of the figures on the cover are missing their heads, broken off and stolen through time. These kinds of texts are vanishingly rare as they are often stolen and sold to collectors. Often when we are enraptured by the magic of cultures as travelers, we easily become the greatest perpetrators of cultural degradation as our lust to 'own' something precious overrides and undermines genuine stewardship. Laws that protect the illegal trade of antiques are porous at best. Demand for authentic antiques drives supply. And while there is nothing inherently wrong with 'owning a piece of history', it's important that we stop to question how things like this are initially 'lost' only to end up being sold to the highest bidder. Photographed #onassigment for @natgeo
